title: Fruit Cage - Protect a ripening apple

description.text:
I grew an apple tree for several years before I managed to make it produce fruit. With only a small number of apples ripening, I'm paranoid some critter is going to tear them all off or nibble them. A gentle deterrent seemed in order, so this little force field, or apple death-star seemed appropriate. Should deter squirrels and birds - maybe deer too?

This should work for a range of fruit applications. I enlarged the stem-hole slightly in this version compared to the photo. The cage is intentionally thin to use minimal material. A bug turned feature is that the cage struts are a bit rough from my printer, but that makes them all the less pleasant for little squirrel hands.

Try on peaches, nectarines, plums, and apricots. May need to stretch the file a bit for a pear. I would be very interested to see an apple that over-grows in the cage, and what interesting mark/shape it attains. :)

Print the same model twice. Each print is a half-shell, with two pins. You need three pins to secure register the parts. But you can skip the pins without adverse effects. A twist tie or rubber band around the top and bottom studs holds it together.

Happy growing.

Printer:

MP Select Mini

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.1mm

Infill:

25%

Notes:

Supports are needed and it will probably print okay at .2mm resolution as well. The thin struts are individually a bit fragile but together it's a rather strong rigid shape. Power of the triangulation.
Don't clean-up the printed model too much, some shaggy sharp bits are a good extra deterrent to tiny hands and deer lips.
Slightly earlier versions before the one shared here. You get two halves. Stick the little pins into the holes and secure w an elastic.

Designed in Blender. Optimized gradually to minimize material usage and adjusted with a test fit to better accommodate leaves on the fruit's stem. Finally installed version 5 and it appears to be functional.

title: HobbyGel - The Parameterised, Makerbot-Printable Gel Casting Kit

description.text:
In the spirit of Open Source Hardware, this design is now compliant with the http://freedomdefined.org/OSHW definition of "Open Source Hardware"! Derivatives are expected to be likewise free.
Gel Electrophoresis is a staple procedure in modern genetic and molecular biology practise. It involves casting a \"gel\" made of Agarose (super-pure Agar, it is possible to just use Agar-Agar also) which contains a dye that binds DNA, and then forcing lengths of DNA through the Gel with a voltage so that they separate by size and collect dye. They can then be photographed and analysed. Electrophoresis requires Agarose/Agar, a Dye (such as the commonly available methyline blue, or the more hazardous Ethidium Bromide or Sybr-Safe/Sybr-Green), and equipment that should only cost about â‚¬50 but is in fact priced closer to â‚¬500 at least. The least of this equipment is the casting set used to make the gel and sit it in the tank of conductive buffer, which is what this Thing comprises. The HobbyGel Casting Kit is composed of a small Gel Boat (with a footprint of 5cm X 6cm) and a selection of \"combs\" used to cast the \"wells\" into which the DNA is injected prior to applying voltage. Depending on the number of samples needing to be Electrophoresed, one can print combs with more teeth or multiple combs. Also included in this Thing is the larger cousin of the HobbyGel, the LabCompat Gel Casting Kit, which is sized to fit the somewhat-standard \"Bio-Rad Mini-Sub Cell-GT\" Electrophoresis Rig. Both sets are available from my shop, Labs From Fabs;
http://www.shapeways.com/shops/labsfromfabs
I have priced them as competitively as I can, so that a full HobbyGel kit comprising a 7-Well Comb and a Casting Boat should cost $59.73 in Europe, less elsewhere. I intend to have both available for order in a choice of either opaque, tough plastic or transluscent acrylic. It is my hope that the latter is UV-permeable enough to allow easy transillumination, while the former will be much cheaper but will call for the trivial additional step of removing the gel from the cast before illuminating with UV. (If required! See below for links to home-brew DNA extraction/visualisation projects requiring no such UV and no Agarose!)

If you want a HobbyGel from your Makerbot, try printing the HobbyGel GelBoat and one of the HobbyGel Combs. I have not yet had a chance to test them, but it is likely that they will require some post-processing to make them practical: You will have to trim back ooze, and even with watertight skeinforge settings it might be helpful to paint on some ABS/acetone glue to smooth out the interior of the casting set and the teeth of the comb so they can easily cast Agar/Agarose without sticking or tearing the Gel. Printing this out of PLA might allow UV-permeability, so that you could mount UV LEDs under your Gel Rig for ease of visualisation..I don\'t yet know, not having any PLA to hand. Feedback welcome if anyone tries this. To make a Gel, Extract DNA from something and visualise it at home with minimal non-household requirements, see this fantastic article from the Science Creative Quarterly:
http://www.scq.ubc.ca/the-macgyver-project-genomic-dna-extraction-and-gel-electrophoresis-experiments-using-everyday-materials/ For another great walkthrough on extracting your own DNA using Rum and washing up liquid, see this Instructable:
http://www.instructables.com/id/5_minute_DNA_Extraction_in_a_Shot_Glass/step7/Tastes-like-DNA/

title: Venus Box Teeth with Leg mod

description.text:
I was having a hell of a time getting the teeth to print for the Venus Box. The little semi-circular hinge seemed to fail every time.

I added a little leg for structural support (mirroring the original, non-toothed design) and that seems to help with the point where the fail occurred.

ALSO - My slicer did something weird with the internal structure where the leg meets the hinge the first time around. You may need to play with your slicer settings to make sure that there's no hollow space inside of the hinge... just verify that your layers make sense, and that this slices as a solid object connected by a tiny bit of material.

description.text:
This is a minimalist mounting bracket solution for the RepRapDiscount Full Graphic Smart Controller (128 x 64 pixels) designed specifically for the BobsCNC RP9 3D printer.

The design is in three parts, requires no supports, and is a very secure fit. It is quite possible that you may even need to tweak the settings to allow your own display to fit, in which case head on over to Tinkercad to create your own modification:
Left bracket:
https://tinkercad.com/things/jNjIqbIlaLJ
Right bracket:
https://tinkercad.com/things/dIhJuMGYNtY
Brace:
https://tinkercad.com/things/gr6kpI4ed7J

The left and right brackets are designed to clip directly onto the PCBs of the display and may be sufficiently tight by themselves. However, the brackets have small tabs in the back to allow the third part, a brace, to be clipped and supported to ensure the brackets don't accidentally loosen up and release the display.

Props where props are due: I got inspiration from the following display brackets:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1680818
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1310171

This, like those, is designed to work with no additional hardware. Print it and use it!

Note - there is either a flaw in the mirror function in Tinkercad or I did something else to the design to cause the width of one side to be deeper than the other. As such, the brace is deeper on one side and will only be able to be fastened one way. I'm too lazy to fix it! :-)

YOU MUST SCALE UP BY 10 TIMES!!!!!!!

This is a small assembly of pieces designed to mount 10mm tubes at the correct spacing to attach the Tarot T4-3D Gimbal.

THIS DOES NOT INCLUDE THE 10mm SHAFT AS MOST 3D PRINTED TUBES ARE FRAGILE

The idea is to mount this onto a drone, In my case the DJI F550, to extend the gimbal past the arms and props so that you have professional video quality with no distractions.

I suggest "Gimbal Mount Test" for mounting to the plate, as it will sit better, while the "Final Small Gimbal" is better suited to epoxy to a plate to mount the battery on.

So far I have only printed one part, and three more are printing as I type, so I don't have a photo of the final use. When I do, it will go up here.

In the future, I also plan to make add to this to make it a detachable handheld gimbal, because I am cheap and cannot afford two gimbals...

description.text:
So, after REALLY much wanting to go and get my printer a cable chain to tidy up the mess of wires and give it a more professional look, while obviously wanting to do them myself, I went off to an epic quest ...

I had found some good models for parametric drag chains, but none of them quite hit my style.
Some were a bit too hard to print, others used print-in-place, or a snap method that required good overhangs and larger parts (and I just don't feel comfy with 'em)
(Though who knows though, maybe there's a nice version somewhere?)

Anyhow, after an afternoon of fun with OpenSCAD, I came up with this!

My pretty much fully parametric, very easy to print, overhang- (not bridge-)less, pretty stable drag chain design!

Printer Brand:

RepRap

Printer:

Prusa i3

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Resolution:

0.2mm layer (for quick printing)

Infill:

No infill here!

Notes:

Configure the chain to whatever wanted /USING VALUES.SCAD/
All important config settings are there, you do not need to touch the other ones!

You can then create the STL for a chain piece with "ChainElement.scad", and an STL for a cable clip of fitting size with "CableClip.scad"

Then, print the different pieces.
You can modify the length of a piece, or the upper or lower angle bounds, while keeping it attachable to the other pieces!

Post-Step 1: Adding the axes

After printing the different drag chain pieces, connect them by inserting a piece of filament through the holes (which can be seen easily in the title picture).
After doing so, cut the filament as close to the pieces as possible, and then either:

  • Carefully glue the filament piece to either the outside or the inside piece or
  • (Recommended) Squeeze the filament piece so that the ends squish and thusly lock it in place.

Why this? Using filament axis is the quickest, easiest, and probably also most stable way to create a rotating piece using 3D printing on small scales!

Post-Step 2: Wiring the cables

Once the chain has gotten the right length, lay out all the wires that will go through it. Make sure that the chain is still flexible, and that everything fits nicely!
Spend some extra time on getting the cables tidy!!

Once that is done too, you can then use the cable clips provided in "CableClip.scad" to fixate them in place.
This makes for a very quick, surprisingly reliable, easy to implement and most importantly: easy to remove way of securing the cables inside the chain!
Should you ever want to redo the wires, just remove the clips, and reinsert them once done!

Contributing

Is this model not good enough?
Have you found a bug or want to tidy up some codes?

Then open up a pull-request of my random-stuff-repository here:
https://www.github.com/xasin/TRRIAN

Twisty Puzzles Museum Entry: http://www.twistypuzzles.com/cgi-bin/puzzle.cgi?pkey=5719

This is my half-turn ‘domino’. It was inspired by Oskar Van Deventer’s Half-Turn Cube, which was originally designed by Takafumi Haseda and made by Hidetoshi Takeji. The half turn cube appears to be just a normal 3x3x3, but is only capable of making 180 degree turns, whereas the traditional puzzle is capable of making turns in increment of ninety degrees.

This is its 3x3x2 equivalent, a domino-type twisty puzzle that is only capable of making these sort of ‘half-turns’. Just like a standard 3x3x2, or any 3x3xn cuboid where n is an even number of layers, this puzzle turns only by increments of 180 degrees on 4 faces, and by increments of 90 on the two remaining faces. However, in this case, the limitation of the first 4 faces has been extended to apply to the top and bottom faces as well.

In order to make it apparent when the cube can and cannot be turned, the middle slice was printed in blue plastic, and the outer slices in this tan color. When the all of the blue pieces are lined up, the puzzle can make a turn on another face. When they are not, they must be lined up again in order for another turn to be made.

In the original half-turn cube, and later on the half-turn tetrahedron, the ‘half-turns only’ functionality was caused by a sort of external and internal bandaging, where pieces came in different sizes that were compatible only with each other. In this case, the bandaging is internal, so it looks just like a normal 3x3x2.

This was designed in Solidworks. The tan pieces were printed on a Makerbot Replicator 5g, and the blue ones on a printrbot simple metal desktop 3D printer.

This is a holder I made for the Nexus 5x with slots in the bottom where I glued in the USBC cable and a headphone jack so I can slide in the phone in the car easily and have it hooked up to power and aux in.

I connect it to the following magnetic rotational mount so I can use it landscape or portrait:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:685687

That is then connected to a mount that I stick in the cd slot on my Honda Fit. I don't have the files for that mount up yet, but I have seen similar things on the site by others.

The holder comes up to a few mm below the volume buttons allowing easy access to everything, including the fingerprint scanner and camera on the back.

This just needs a little filing/sanding to remove any rough edges so it does not scratch the back surface of the phone. Easy to do with a file or course sandpaper. I have been using it for several days on a black nexus 5x and an ABS print and have not seen any scratching on the phone yet.

  2. Adding a large shaft driven gear

  4. added a high clearance b'struder arm

title: RPi tray with captive M3 nuts

description.text:
The changes to the original are as follows:
  • Added cut outs for a pair of M3 nuts underneath so that the Pi can be attached though the original holes using M3 x 8mm screws
  • Increased the width of one of the struts carrying one of the mounting holes. (Photos show an earlier incarnation - the attached STL is has the wider strut).
    • I made these changes in order to attach a RPi to my Mendel90 dibond kit from Nophead. The Pi Tray was fixed using double sided tape to the top of the PSU and the Pi itself fixed in place using a couple of 8mm screws and washers. This keeps all the electronics together and enables the use of a short USB lead from the MELZI to the Pi. I have powered mine using the +5V PSU wires which were cut short and covered with heatshrink during assembly of the kit.

Please note that the STL has what appears to be a shelf between the mounting holes and the nut trap. This is intentional - without it, the mounting holes would not print correctly as their diameter is less than that of the hex shapes for the nuts below them.  
Print and then fit two M3 nuts into the gaps at the bottom. Once the nuts are in place you can use a drill bit to remove the thin support material described above.  
If using this with a Mendel90, use double sided tape to attach it to the top of the PSU, press down firmly and then attach your Pi using two M3 x 8mm screws and washers.

Electrical engineers work with anything that carries electricity. They are responsible for designing many of the things you use every day (computers, cell phones, etc.)

In this activity, students will take on the role of an electrical engineer and explore the concept of open & closed circuits. They will use simple materials to design and build a Circuit Maze.

The 3D printed parts were designed in Tinkercad, but many different 3D modeling programs should work well for this. There are a few examples included in the Thing Files.

Prompt students to design their own 3D Printed Circuit Enclosure - see sample below.

The object is for students to design a maze out of conductive material (maze material) that you can navigate with a conductive object (maze navigator). The goal is to not touch the material as you pass it through the navigator. If you do, a light (or sound) should signal that the circuit has been closed. The bulk of the circuit should be housed within a 3D printed custom circuit enclosure. See additional info in Handouts attached in the Thing Files. Objectives Students should walk away with knowledge of:
  • Basic circuit design
  • Creating a proper circuit diagram
  • Designing and building a custom enclosure using 3D printing
    • Skills Learned (Standards) High School
  • HS-PS3-3 Design, build, and refine a device that works within given constraints to convert one form of energy into another form of energy.
    • Middle School
  • MS-ETS1-1 - Define the criteria and constraints of a design problem with sufficient precision to ensure a successful solution, taking into account relevant scientific principles and potential impacts on people and the natural environment that may limit possible solutions.
  • MS-ETS1-2 - Evaluate competing design solutions using a systematic process to determine how well they meet the criteria and constraints of the problem.
  • MS-ETS1-3 - Analyze data from tests to determine similarities and differences among several design solutions to identify the best characteristics of each that can be combined into a new solution to better meet the criteria for success.
  • MS-ETS1-4 - Develop a model to generate data for iterative testing and modification of a proposed object, tool, or process such that an optimal design can be achieved.

1. Preparation:
  • Have students gather all of their project materials
  • I had students work in groups of 2 on this project.
    • 2. Provide PROMPT (also on Student Handout): The object is to design a maze out of your Maze Material (some conductive material) that you can navigate with your Maze Navigator (paperclip, or similar conductive object). The general goal is to have other students play your game by moving the Maze Navigator through the maze without touching the Maze Material (try to make it difficult, but not impossible). However, if they do touch - a sound, light, or some other device should signal that the circuit has been closed. There are many different ways you can interpret this prompt, get creative! See a few examples in the pictures above. 3. Review Requirements for Project See Student Handout for Maze Requirements and Flyer Requirements 4. Review Sample projects & Project Timeline:
  • DEMO Circuit Maze - build your own or show the pictures/videos above.
  • See more in References section below.
    • 5. Working sessions - Building the Mazes:
  • I allotted 3 in-class working days to this project (and an additional 2 days if students needed to finish their design at home or after school)
  • Make sure to emphasize the multiple ways that students can build mazes and still fulfill the Maze Requirements
  • As students finish their circuit design, they should begin considering how they are going to build their enclosure to house their circuit, taking any necessary measurements of their power source, connectors, LED's, etc.
    • 6. Working sessions - Building the Circuit Enclosure:
  • This can be done with many materials, but I prompted students to design and 3D print a custom enclosure for their circuit.
  • Students should try to house the majority of their circuit within and enclosure, though there will likely be some wires, LEDs, etc. that live outside of the enclosure.
  • I used Tinkercad to design the sample enclosure, see screenshot below.
    • 7. Flyers and Final Presentations:
  • Students should create a flyer describing the rules of their maze and a proper circuit diagram of their circuit design (see Student Handout for more detailed info on requirements).
  • Finally, students present their designs and take turns trying each other's mazes!
    • Optional: Prototype Circuit Design in Autodesk Circuits Autodesk Circuits is an awesome free program that allows you to prototype and simulate circuit designs before actually building them. For students interested in exploring more complex circuit designs for this project, it could be a great tool to help them discover and test their ideas. Testing out a circuit design in Autodesk Circuits Designing a Custom 3D Printed Circuit Enclosure in Tinkercad

  • Conductive “Maze Navigator” Ex) Paperclip, nail, tin foil-wrapped pen
  • Base Material: Ex) Cardboard box, foam board,
  • Wire – for creating circuit
  • Use wires with alligator clips (or a breadboard) to avoid the need for soldering
  • Light or Buzzer – for signaling when the circuit is complete: Ex) LED, simple buzzer, etc.
  • Battery
  • CAUTION!! – Teacher should double check circuit design BEFORE connecting battery or power supply
  • 3D Printed Circuit Enclosure - a custom enclosure built to house the main parts of the circuit design. More instructions on this below.

description.text:
Stormtrooper V2

Thanks to mchau2 from Instructables for the original. Unfortunately, his original model was practically unprintable. This remix is much easier to print, although still challenging.

NOTE the Zip file contains the entire model, broken into separate parts.

In several cases, parts are duplicated for various reasons, mostly related to the fact that this was a tough model to print, so it took more than a few retries.

Some parts have variants with built-in supports, some need raft enabled.

You do not need to print all of the duplicated parts.
I incremented the part name (knees-v2, knees-v3, etc.) in cases where I had difficulty.

So, I recommend starting with the highest version numbers first.
(You will notice "legs.stl" and "legs-V3.stl" but no V2 due to flaws that made me discard the V2 version.)

Generally, print with raft if the part has a small surface area touching the bed. (I was able to print most of the parts without raft.)

I recommend printing the parts that have a "+support" name. These can be printed without added support. If you choose to print the +support parts, you can ignore the variants that would otherwise require the addition of supports.

You are likely to encounter some issues, even with all the re-plating and rotating I've done.
For example, I had to use a heat gun to make the torso fit properly below the chest area, and the original neck part seemed ludicrously long -- I printed an extra copy of a shorter ball-joint part for it instead.

I recommend using black filament for the skeleton and gloves and white for the suit.

IMPORTANT
The sides of the lower arm and lower leg sockets will probably require trimming
(I used a Dremel tool) in order to fit inside the wrist/ankle sleeves.

You may wish to trim the sides of the sockets on these parts directly to solve this problem instead of taking this 'brute force' approach. But using the Dremel was faster. :-)

Good luck.

For More Information

description.text: Pop Pop Boats are a small scale demonstration of a steam engine. This project is a remix of the 3D Printed Pop Pop Boat. I've added plugs to keep the water in the primed engine and modified the engine to print well using #MeshMixer. Having groups of students build the Putt Putt (PopPop) Boats enables them to get hands-on up-close interaction with the components of their simple steam engine. This is a great #ScienceProject for helping students develop understanding of thermodynamic cycles, phase changes, and transfer of energy.

Printer Brand:

MakerBot

Printer:

Rafts:

Supports:

To build the pop-pop boat, you will need the 3D printed Hull.STL, Engine.STL, and two StrawPlugs.STL; two 5 mm bendable drinking straws; heavy duty aluminum foil; plastic glue with an activator; high temp glue; water sealant (optional); a tea light candle (and something to light it with) and some pennies or nickels to add ballast. When you print the boat and the engine, it will take about four hours at the #Makerbot standard settings. If you are concerned about the porosity of a 3D printed boat, use some water sealant on the hull of the main body.

While that is drying, clear the flashing around the straw holes on the engine. Trim about a half an inch off the short end of the straws and about two inches off the long end. Then insert the two straws through the slanted holes at the edge of the engine. Fully extend the flexible membrane of the straws, then position them so that you can insert the short end flush with the holes on the top of the engine. Follow the instructions for the plastic glue to glue these ends into the holes. The goal is to have the engine be a pressurized vessel, so the seal around the ends of the straws must be glued well. Allow that to dry per package instructions.

Next, lay out a piece of the aluminum flat on the table in front of you. Follow the instructions on the high temp glue and layer it on to the rim of the engine. Once it is sufficiently coated, lower it on top of the aluminum foil and press to get a solid seal between the engine and the foil. Allow this to dry then trim the excess foil away from the engine.

To fire up your boat, you will need to have water in the engine before you start. It’s hard to get the water to go into the straws, so get one of those picnic condiment bottles or a syringe for oral medicine to squirt the water down one straw until you see water coming back out the second straw. Insert the caps into both straws to keep the water where you put it.

Place a few coins in the side slots at the rear of the boat to help keep it low in the water. The two quarters I used in the demo had it a little too low, so I recommend nickels or pennies. Place the tea-light candle in the central circle, place the boat in the water, and light the candle. Place the engine over top of the candle so the ends of the straws are submerged and the engine snaps down into its bracket. Then pull the plugs from the straws.

It will take a minute or two for the water to get heated up well enough to propel the boat. You’ll see a few bubbles escape early, but be patient, it will start puttering around once the water is hot enough to begin a steam-cool cycle.

This is a remix of the 3D Printed Pop Pop Boat. I’ve added #MeshMixer supports to make the engine an easier print and I used #OnShape to add a plug design (print two!) to put into the straws after you’ve primed the engine with water. Below are ideas for using this as a #ScienceProject.

Steam engines use the expansion of steam to drive propulsion.  Using this simple example of a steam engine, students will be able to observe a thermodynamic cycle in action. The fire of the candle heats up the water inside the engine, which becomes hot enough to change phase into steam.  When the steam expands, it drives water out of the straws, into the pool of cooler water.  This cooler water absorbs the heat from the steam, causing it to change phase back into water, reducing its volume and drawing more cooler water into the system.  The fluctuations in volume cause the aluminum foil to expand and contract, creating the popping noise that you hear as the engine is active.

This project should take about 3 hours, but the assembly has to dry overnight, so allow one hour for assembly and theory; a second hour on another day for running the boat, discussions, and student group work; then a third hour (same day or another) for coming together as a class to share group findings. Print a boat, engine, and two straw plugs for each group of students. Supply them with the necessary materials so that they can perform the boat construction once or while you review the theory behind steam engines. Steam engines take advantage of the high specific heat of vaporization of water and the expansion that occurs during this phase change. SciToys offers a great explanation of how steam engines work, as does ScienceToyMaker, with a more elementary presentation and a focus on hands-on explanations of the fundamental concepts. Ask the students to explain to you what they believe will occur with the putt putt boat and identify the key components for that result. When you do fire up the putt putt boats and observe their behavior, you can discuss, qualitatively, what is happening. This How Things Work article, this article, and this webpage are great resources for discussing the forces and actors involved in propelling the Putt Putt Boat. At some point in discussing these forces, you will come to the question, “Why doesn’t the suction caused by the condensing steam suck the boat backwards?” There have been a lot of articles and research studies on this topic! This paper gives the most succinct explanation and has a few diagrams to help make its point. After students have observed their boats and asked questions that inspire further research, provide them with an opportunity to conduct that research and share with the class. You can ask your students to develop models of the system, drawing diagrams or illustrations that identify key components and events that cause the transfer of energy from the heat of the flame to the propulsion of the boat. You could also ask them to develop a method for determining the work done by the engine (through the change in kinetic energy); you could ask them to determine the efficiency of their engine (This can be a good resource for that investigation); or you could ask them to develop experiments involving the temperature of the water, the type of fuel, or the draft of the boat in the water. For an engineering focus, you could ask the students to design a better version or to consider (and design/build) ones that use differently sized straws. The question of straw size can be tied in to AP Physics 2 topics in fluid dynamics as well.

Students can be assessed on applying the scientific method to determining the influence of water temperature, straw diameter, or other adjustments through lab reports or presentations.  
Students can be assessed on understanding of thermodynamic cycles and heat engines through the assignment of creating drawings and/or diagrams of the processes.
Students can be assessed on accuracy and precision in analysis and calculations of work and efficiency.

Objectives

Upon completion of this project, students will be able to demonstrate an understanding of heat engines and the thermodynamic cycle, including the vocabulary relevant to changes in temperature, pressure, and volume. They should be able to identify the components that are actors in the thermodynamic cycle and they should be able to create a graph of the cycle that occurs.
